Declarative Code
There is a div with class 'red' and text 'Hi there'
You!  Go make a div.  Give it a class of 'red'.  Also, give it some text of 'Hi there'
We are telling the browser exactly how to create a div
We are telling the browser the final state.  It is up to the browser to figure out how to achieve that
Imperative Code
Declarative Code
There is a collection of data called 'users'
You!  Find all the users in this array with an age greater than 15
A portion of users have an age above 15
We are telling our program exactly how to find users with an age over 25
We are telling our program the dataset we want to see.  It is up to the program to figure out how to get this dataset
Every declarative program relies upon an imperative program
Developers like declarative systems because we can generally write less code
Creating a system to interpret declarative code probably takes more time than just writing an imperative program
There's a difference between using a declarative system (us writing HTML) vs creating a declarative system (people writing Chrome)
